post_text: Tomorrow is a big day, and we couldn't be more ready. Orientation for all grades begins tomorrow morning over Zoom, and our Family Support Center opens at our Middle School campus to provide extra support for students whose growth depends most-heavily on in-person instruction, including English Language Learners, students with Individualized Education Plans, and students in families that depend on childcare to work. Students who participate in the Family Support Center will work collaboratively in small, socially-distanced advisory groups with the support of a staff member. Whether online or in person, we can not wait to see you tomorrow, students! Check our website for orientation schedules and a full September calendar: inwoodacademy.org/events #inwoodacademy

post_text:
Today is #InternationalLiteracyDay, a holiday created by the United Nations in 1966 to promote literacy for children and adults globally, and we want to give a shout out to all the readers and lifelong learners we get the honor of teaching here at Inwood Academy for Leadership. We are grateful for the perseverance of our students who come to us as new readers and/or learning English as a new language, and we are excited to carry on the joyful work of teaching you this year. If you didn’t get a chance before, check out our #inwoodreads and #inwoodwrites blog that our students created last May to showcase their work. #inwoodacademy #readersmakeleaders
http://www.inwoodreadsinwoodwrites.org

post_text:
Happy #LaborDay from Inwood Academy! Labor Day first became a national holiday in the late 19th Century as a response to an ongoing Worker’s Rights movement, and today, we want to take a moment to thank all those who have fought for fair work and wages in our country. Inwood Academy employs over 150 staff members each year and works tirelessly to ensure the wellbeing of each staff member so that they can in turn care for our students.

One of the reasons we are opening our Family Support Center next week is to prioritize and serve students whose families rely on childcare to work in the midst of this pandemic. We are so grateful for the diversity of services that allow us to teach our next generation’s leaders day in, day out, and we are committed as a school to promoting wellness and equity for all learners and workers in our world. ✊✊✊

post_text:
Ten Year Staff Spotlight: John Harrison
At the time we opened Inwood Academy, we had an overwhelming amount of applications for every open position. There was a hiring freeze at the NYC DOE and it was a tough time to be a teacher. During this hiring process, one amazing teacher, John Harrison, saw something unique in Inwood that he found exciting and decided to take a chance on us. He adjusted his classroom practice to support a different group of learners than he had taught previously and spoke into school policy. He pioneered our woodshop program with a small group of high school students and grew it to what it is today - a one-of-a-kind space for students to grow creatively and gain confidence outside the classroom. Our students see Mr. Harrison as an older brother and even a father figure. We are so thankful that he took a chance on IAL. We are all forever blessed to have him in our lives. #inwoodacademy #inwood10

post_text:
We want to use this momentary pause that summer vacation brings us to continue honoring the staff members who have been with us since we opened our doors ten years ago! Meet Aurea Lopez (pictured with her family):

When our founder Christina Reyes was still in the planning stages with Inwood Academy, she got her first iPhone and recorded Aurea Lopez's number with the title "Future IAL Employee." We knew we would need Aurea on board as a teacher as soon as we opened IAL. She had an impressive track record of success, especially working with students who struggle behaviorally and academically. She cares for the "furthest out" students and loves them like her own children. Over the past ten years, Aurea’s students have learned so much, not just about academics, but about life. She has changed students' views of themselves and helped them realize that they CAN when many of them thought they could NEVER. Thank you Aurea for your heart for and commitment to our students. You are an inspiration. #inwoodacademy #inwood10

post_text:
This year did not go or end according to plan. It was full of surprises at every turn, and for many, full of struggle. One thing we have not been surprised by is the incredible resilience of our students, families and staff, and for this reason, we end the year celebrating.

Thank you students for continuing to engage, learn and show up under incredibly difficult circumstances; we are amazed by your perseverance and self-leadership. Thank you teachers for your tireless hours reworking curriculum, hosting office hours, and doing whatever is necessary to meet each student where they are during this time. And thank you, as always, to the many supporters in and out of our community who help make this work possible every day. We are hopeful for another great year, whatever it may bring. Now go enjoy some much-deserved rest, and happy summer vacation! #inwoodacademy #inwood10

post_text: 155 years ago today, the news finally reached Galveston, Texas that the Civil War had ended and the enslaved we now free; this was two and a half years after the Emancipation Proclamation was signed abolishing slavery nationwide. At Inwood Academy, we recognize the intricate systems that still delay freedom for Black Americans, and we are committed to the long work of providing equitable education and opportunity for all people. We believe the way we teach history to our children directly impacts the way they shape our future, and so today we observe Freedom Day, celebrating the progress we have made and pressing on toward the progress we still have yet to make. #blacklivesmatteratschool

post_text:
Our next #Classof2020 spotlight student is Edward Peralta, who will be studying at College of Mount Saint Vincent this fall.

"I’m excited to join many diverse clubs at my new school. While I’m at College of Mount Saint Vincent, one of my goals will be to maintain an above average GPA and grow as an individual. I will dearly miss socializing with my classmates and the staff at IAL. They were the people who made my high school experience one that I’ll never forget. I would like to shout out Mr. Garcia and Mr. Tejeda for assisting and supporting me through my college application process. I can’t imagine how I would have gotten through it without them. I am excited about opening this new chapter in my life where I will be getting closer to achieving my career goals. I aspire to become more independent and set an example for my younger sister. Thanks Inwood Academy for preparing me for the next step in my life." Congratulations, Edward, and all graduating seniors! #covidgraduation #inwoodacademy

post_text:
Happy 50th annual Earth Day from Inwood Academy for Leadership!

50 years ago today, on April 22, 1970, over 20 million people gathered across the country to demonstrate their commitment to our earth and future fellowman. This effort is nowhere close to over, but we still have hope.

A silver lining fact during our pandemic: carbon emissions are falling quickly due to world-wide quarantine immobility, and endangered animals are even re-inhabiting their former homes.

Tragedies and chaos come, but the earth never ceases to amaze us. Thank you to all of the environmentalists and activists who advocate every day for our collective future, and we hope you can experience from your small window of the world the beauty of our earth today.

Photo by Trent Szmolnik on Unsplash

#EarthDay

Our next #IALessentialworkershoutout goes to IAL parent Ana de Jesus!

Ana is the mom of Julian Corona (6th grade), Julio Corona (8th grade), and Juliana Corona (10th grade) and she works as a therapist in a healthcare facility.

“I fight to protect the elderly and people with different disabilities from depression, loneliness, boredom, confusion caused by dementia, frustration and fear because they can't see their family. I provide them with special psycho/social support in this difficult time.”

Thank you Ana and all #frontlineworkers!

post_text:
Today we began Phase 2 of our online learning plan and we continue to be proud of our students and staff for working hard through these adjustments.

As much as is possible during this time, we always want you to know what's next, and so here's an update on Phase 3 and Regents testing.

This afternoon at the daily press conference, Governor Cuomo announced a continuation and extension of "pause," through April 29, 2020, meaning we will remain closed as a school until then. Phase 3 remote learning will begin on April 20th.

Also today, at the NYS Board of Regents meeting, Chancellor Rosa announced that the June Regents exams will be canceled. Additional guidance on this matter will be released soon.

For more COVID-19 Updates, visit our website here: https://inwoodacademy.org/coronavirus-update/

We look forward to re-opening our doors as soon as it is safe to do so.

post_text:
“I fell in love with Inwood Academy as soon as I walked through its doors seven years ago. In the morning my kids used to give me a tough time about going to school, but once they started going to Inwood Academy, they just loved going.

“When my daughter first came to Inwood Academy, she was below fifth grade reading level, and I am proud to say that after just a few years of support at Inwood Academy, she is now in AP English. My boys have overcome social and emotional obstacles and developed their leadership skills.

“My children have very different learning styles and needs. My main concern as a mom when they started school was making sure they would all three be able to thrive. The magic of Inwood Academy is that they have all been able to thrive in their own way.”

Jhoselyn's triplets will graduate from our high school next Spring, each equipped for their own unique form of success. Set your child up for a future full of choice by applying now for our 2020-21 school year.

https://inwoodacademy.org/admissions/

Lottery application closes tonight 11:59p.m.

REMOTE LEARNING UPDATE

This Wednesday we will begin remote learning with all grades, and here are some different ways you can prepare:

In addition to computers, tablets and phones, students can access Google classrooms from PS4 and Xbox One browsers.

For families who don’t have internet service, Spectrum and Optimum are offering free service and setup for two months in certain areas. Please call 1-844-488-8398 (Spectrum) or 866-200-9522 (Optimum), ask for the sales department, and give them your address to see if you qualify.

If you don’t have any device with which you can access Google classrooms, please email jenny.pichardo@ialcs.org or text 347-501-1414 now so we can print a paper package for your child. You can pick up these packets from IAL tomorrow (Tuesday) between 3 and 6pm.

post_text: Due to the expanding nature of the current COVID-19 pandemic, we will be closing school to students Monday, March 16th. All classes will move to an online format as of Wednesday, March 18th and will continue this way until Spring Break. We know this is going to pose a large challenge for everyone, and we will be supporting our families in many ways through this time. You can read more about this update on our website (https://inwoodacademy.org/coronavirus-update) and contact Tatiana Mahoney at tatiana.mahoney@ialcs.org with any needs you may have during this transition.

post_text:
Ten Year Staff Spotlight: Val Hoekstra

In 2008, before we opened our doors, Valerie Hoekstra signed up as one of the very first on a team of people crazy enough to follow this dream of starting a school uptown. Inwood Academy was still very much an idea at the time, with so much work still to be done. Val started as a special education specialist and eventually stepped into leadership as our Middle School Principal. She is an amazing leader, a trusted advisor, and a dependable resource to our students, working to meet their unique and ever-present needs in so many different ways. Without Val, Inwood Academy would not be the place it is, especially the place it is for students with special needs, full of support, understanding and resources. Thank you, Val, for everything you have done and continue to do for our school. #inwoodacademy #inwood10

post_text: Readers make leaders, and so we do all we can to foster a love of reading in our students, regardless of their starting reading level. In our middle school, we are developing in-class libraries that allow students to read independently and check out books to bring home. So far, our libraries represent over 12 different genres and reading levels, and our students love to choose their own books! #inwoodacademy #NationalGrammarDay

"When I remember ten years have passed since we first opened our doors to 100 fifth grade students, I am overcome with amazement and gratitude. I run for many more years of Inwood Academy for Leadership."

post_text:
#BlackHistoryMonth weekly leadership spotlight:

William H. Hatsie started his career as a practicing Lawyer and teacher at Howard University before he received a doctorate in Judicial Studies at Harvard. He served as federal judge for the Virgin Islands under the Roosevelt administration, becoming the first black American federal judge, and in 1949 he accepted President Truman’s nomination for the Federal Court of Appeals. Hastie’s nomination met resistance and took six months to be confirmed, but he served as judge from 1950 to 1971. William Hastie became one of the most respected members of the court, and he used his position of influence to support the public good until his death in 1976. #trailblazers

Ten Year Staff spotlight: Ashley Carabaugh

Ashley was Inwood Academy's first paid staff member (aside from our founder) and she started with us when we were still meeting at tiny desk in the Charter Center downtown. She helped us do just about everything to get off the ground - choose our insurance company, create school policies, hire teachers, set up bank accounts - and since then she has been a devoted teacher, stepping in wherever needed, even leading our choir! Ashley has sacrificed to serve IAL in too many ways to count, and we would not be the same without her. #inwoodacademy #inwood10

Meet our #NYCHalfMarathon Runner, Jenny Pichardo!

"As a Dominican-American who grew up with immigrant parents in Washington Heights, I can relate to our students, our school community, and I love that our students can see themselves represented in Leadership at their school. My son was a part of Inwood Academy's 2nd graduating class in 2019, and so as both a parent and as Inwood Academy's COO/CFO, I get to teach our students the importance of education and giving back to their community. I love the impact we have on students’ lives, and the way we are cemented in our community. We have created a positive place for the community to gather. At Inwood Academy we care about every single person; the moment you enroll as a student, you become a member of the IAL family. I am running for the future of our growing IAL family and community at large. Please support me as I run by giving to my gofundme campaign": https://charity.gofundme.com/o/en/campaign/inwood-academy-of-leadership-nyc-half-2020/jennypichardo2
#inwoodacademy #inwood10

post_text:
#BlackHistoryMonth weekly leadership spotlight:

Born in Texas in 1892, Bessie Coleman was the first black American female pilot. She trained in some of the best aviation schools in Europe and earned her international pilot’s license in 1921. “Queen Bess,” as she was nicknamed, quickly became famous for her daredevil tricks, taking many risks throughout her career, and eventually passing away prematurely because of a mechanical failure in 1926. Coleman had hoped to start a flight school to inspire other young African Americans to fly, and though she was never able to open the school, she has inspired many new generations of pilots. #trailblazers

Meet our #nychalfmarathon runner, board member Elyssa Siminerio!

“I’ve been on the Board of Inwood Academy since its early formation in 2011 and I have watched the school grow from 100 fifth grade students to over 1,000 students and alumni. This will be my fourth year running for Inwood Academy in the NYC Half Marathon, and it goes without saying, if it weren’t for this amazing school and its tireless leadership, I would not push myself to do this year after year. More importantly, if not for this amazing school, 1,000+ students would be missing out on the education that will afford them a future full of opportunity. So I run for these deserving students, for all they have accomplished, and for all they have yet to achieve. Thank you so much for any support and encouragement as we run.”

You can support Elyssa as she runs by following the link in our bio and giving to her gofundme campaign. #inwoodacademy #inwood10

post_text:
#BlackHistoryMonth weekly leadership spotlight:

Matthew Henson was a pioneer Arctic explorer and the first person to reach the North Pole. He began traveling the world when he walked to Baltimore at age 11 to find work as a cabin boy on a freighter ship, which took him to see places like Eastern Asia, Europe and North Africa. Henson learned how to read and write on the ship, becoming a passionate learner, and this curiosity led him to eventually become the only Arctic explorer to learn the native language and gain the local peoples' trust in Arctic expeditions. Though he was the first person to reach the North Pole, he did not receive the same recognition as the commander who accompanied him, and he ended up having to find new work parking cars in New York. He finally was recognized as co-founder of the North Pole by the time he died in 1955. #trailblazers

In continued celebration of our ten year anniversary, we want to thank the staff members who have been with us from the beginning. They each have an unbelievable devotion to the students we serve, and they make us who we are as a school. First up: Nancy Betances (left)!

Nancy has been "mom" since the very start. She is devoted, loyal, and always ready to support change that needs to happen, even when change is hard. Nancy has taken students to doctor appointments, sewn up holes in clothes, and given out candy to get students through a hard day. She not only cares about the students at IAL, but has a deep care for the adults in the building as well. She knows how important the little things are - coffee being number one on that list! :) Thank you Nancy for the care and love that you have shown to everyone for the past ten years. We couldn't do what we do without you. #inwoodacademy #inwood10

post_text:
In honor of #BlackHistoryMonth and our school wide commitment to courageous leadership, we want to take this month to highlight some notable black leaders you may not have learned about in school.

Referred to as the mother of civil rights in California, Mary Ellen Pleasant grew as an entrepreneur and activist throughout the 19th Century. She used her savvy investments to sue streetcar companies in San Francisco who practiced discrimination and defend those who were taken advantage of. As a woman of color in the Civil War Era, her powerful philanthropy and public support of Civil Rights made her a hero for many. #trailblazers

This month’s workshops addressed bullying prevention, understanding grief and loss, substance use prevention, and special education resources. It was so special to hear from you and partner to support your kids, and we are already looking forward to next month.
